# SEO Implementation Plan — Generative Art Website

This document describes the **current refactoring stage** required to prepare the website for proper search engine indexing while preserving the existing architecture.

The site architecture remains:

shell + registry + runtime-loaded artwork modules

Key design rule:
The **registry (registry.js) remains the single source of truth** for all artworks. Runtime navigation, SEO pages, sitemap generation and automation will all derive from it.

Goal:
Expose crawlable pages for each artwork without breaking the minimal JS runtime architecture, and keep the `/all/` page as an indexable list only (no extra descriptions).

URL style rule:
Folder pages use a trailing slash (`/all/`, `/credits/`). Artwork pages are files (`/works/<slug>.html`).

---

# Task 1 — Replace hash routing with crawlable URLs

## Current state

URLs use hash routing:

```
#/work/blur-dots
```

Search engines typically treat this as a single page.

## Target result

Each artwork must have a **real crawlable URL**.

Preferred structure:

```
/works/blur-dots.html
/works/random-walk.html
/works/looped-curve.html
```

## Implementation principle

The site should move to **path-based routing as the primary routing model**. The shared runtime must resolve the current artwork or static section directly from `location.pathname`.

Outcome:
Search engines can directly request artwork pages.

---

# Task 2 — Introduce SEO wrapper pages for artworks

Create thin HTML wrapper pages for each artwork.

Example structure:

```
/works/blur-dots.html
/works/random-walk.html
/works/looped-curve.html
```

These pages act as **SEO entry points** while still using the same runtime shell and the same path-based routing model.

## Implementation principle

All wrapper pages should be based on **one shared template structure**. The pages differ only by a small set of variables:

• slug
• title
• description
• OpenGraph metadata

Everything else should remain identical across pages.

This allows the site to:

• avoid maintaining many different HTML files
• keep the runtime architecture consistent
• unify routing, SEO pages, sitemap and internal links around one URL model
• prepare the project for future automatic page generation

## Responsibilities of each wrapper page

Each page must:

• declare SEO metadata
• load the main runtime shell
• expose the artwork under a real page path

The shared runtime reads the current slug from `location.pathname` and then loads the correct artwork module from `registry.js`.

## Practical rule

SEO wrapper pages **do not render the artwork themselves**. They only declare page metadata and start the shared runtime.

Outcome:
Each artwork has a standalone crawlable page, the runtime resolves content from real paths, and duplication of HTML is minimized.

